This paper is about transition-based dependency parsing, which is a natural language processing task. Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of bi-directional LSTM features, which are commonly used in machine learning and deep learning, suggesting that cs.LG (Machine Learning) is also a likely sub-category. Additionally, the paper presents global training methods, which are related to optimization and learning algorithms, indicating that cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) are also possible sub-categories. Finally, the paper mentions achieving the best results on the Chinese Treebank and the English Penn Treebank, which are datasets commonly used in natural language processing and computer vision, suggesting that cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is a less likely but still possible sub-category.
